<p>You can view and copy the source of this page:
</p><textarea readonly="" accesskey="," id="wpTextbox1" cols="80" rows="25" style="" lang="en" dir="ltr" name="wpTextbox1">[[Category:Tutorials]]
[[Category:Blueprint]]
[[Category:Epic Created Content]]

{{warning|This tutorial is a work in progress. There is a lot of content still being worked on.}}
==Overview==

A generic tank is built with treads, a hull, a turret and a cannon. In this tutorial we will be explaining how to create a complete simple tank that uses the mouse to swivel the turret and pitch the camera independent from the body's movement. 

This tutorial is a pet project of the Unreal Engine Support team. We intend to give all of the basics of creating a tank, but as we go on we plan on adding additional functions that a tank would have.

==Initial Setup==

1. First you will want to make sure that you have a couple of ''Input Axis'' created to make things simpler. You will need to make 4 in total: 

[[File:InputAxis Tank.jpg|left|970px]]
&lt;br clear=all>

*'''Move Forward''' - Used to move the Hull forward/backward.
*'''Rotate Right''' - Used for the Hull's ''Yaw'' rotation. Right(D) returns positive Float values, Left(A) returns negative.
*'''MouseRotateRight''' - Used for the Turret's ''Yaw'' rotation.
*'''MouseLookUp''' - Used for the Cannon's ''Pitch'' rotation. Note that this is actually set to -1 instead of 1. This will actually make sure that the ''Pitch'' rotation is inverted, but if you like standard rotation (Moving the mouse forward tilts the cannon up), leave this positive.

2. Create a new Blueprint based on the Character Class, name it "MyTank" and open it up.

==Hull==

This will be the body that is driven by the WASD controls. 'A' and 'D' will rotate the body in place, while 'W' and 'S' will move the tank back and forth based on the body's rotation.

===Component===

First things first, you will need a few meshes to work with. For this part, all you need is a Hull (I am using a box mesh, but anything works). Since we are using a Character, the Hull will need to be a Skeletal Mesh, but it will have no bones, so import it as a ''Skeletal Mesh'' with ''Rigid Body'' checked on.

In the MyTank Blueprint, assign the Hull to the ''Mesh'' component's ''Skeletal Mesh''. Adjust it into a position that you like.

[[File:HullComp Tank.jpg|Left|970px]]
&lt;br clear=all>

===EventGraph===

====Hull Rotation====

# Open the EventGraph
# Right-click and search for "InputAxis"
# To make this easier, click the small stars next to the different ''InputAxis'' Events to favorite them
# Add an ''InputAxis RotateRight'' node
# Drag off of the ''Axis Value'' and create a ''Make Rot''
# Plug the ''Axis Value'' into the ''Yaw''
# Add a ''Get'' for the Mesh component
# Drag off the ''Mesh'' node and create an ''Add Relative Rotation'' node
# Plug the ''RotateRight'' execution into the ''Add Relative Rotation''
# Plug the ''Make Rot'' into the ''Delta Rotation''

====Hull Movement====

# Add an ''InputAxis MoveForward'' node
# Drag off execution pin and create a ''Add Movement Input'' node
# Plug the ''Axis Value'' pin into the ''Scale Value'' Input
# Drag off of the ''Mesh'' node and create a ''Get World Rotation'' node
# Drag off of ''Return Value'' on the ''Get World Rotation'' node and create a ''Break Rot'' node
# Drag off of ''Yaw'' output and create a ''Make Rot'' node
# Drag off of ''Return Value'' output and create a ''Get Forward Vector'' node
# Plug ''Return Value'' output into world direction of the ''Add Movement Input'' node

[[File:HullMovement Tank.jpg|left|970px]]
&lt;br clear=all>

==Turret==

The turret rests on top of the Hull mesh, swiveling with the movement of the mouse. The camera will follow this movement to make sure the player can see where they are firing. It will also allow for the Hull to move in one direction while the Cannon fires in another.

===Component===

The turret only rotates on the Yaw axis, that is its only function. Since this will be the best way of looking around, the camera should follow its movement.

# Add a ''Static Mesh Component'' parented under the ''Mesh'' component that holds the Hull
# Name this "Turret"
# Move the Turret to fit onto the Hull
# Add a ''Camera Component'' parented under the Turret
# In the ''Camera Component'' uncheck "Use Controller View Rotation"
# Move the ''Camera Component'' so that it is up and behind the entire tank

[[File:TurretAndCamComp Tank.jpg|left|970px]]
&lt;br clear=all>

===EventGraph===
====Turret Rotation====

# Add a '''InputAxis MouseRotateRight''' event node
# Add a '''Get''' for the Turret component
# Drag off the '''Get''' and add a '''Add Relative Roation''' node
# Connect the Execution from the '''MouseRotateRight''' into the '''Add Relative Rotation'''
# Drag off the '''MouseRotateRight''' node's ''Axis Value'' and create a '''Float * Float''' node
# Set the value to multiply by to 1.5(This merely increases the rate of rotation, as the unaltered delta value is quite small)
# Drag off the Float output of the multiplying node and create a '''Make Rot''' node
# Connect the output of the multiply into the ''Yaw'' of the '''Make Rot'''
# Connect the ''Return Value'' of the '''Make Rot''' into the ''Delta Rotation'' or the '''Add Relative Roation'''

[[File:TurretRotation Tank.jpg|left|970px]]
&lt;br clear=all>

==Cannon==

The Cannon will ''Pitch'' up and down while rotating with the Turret's ''Yaw''. It will use the mouse's movement, like the Turret, but only the Y-Axis movement. Unlike the Hull and Turret, the Cannon will only rotate between certain degrees so that it will not spin into the Hull and Turret.

===Component===

This will be the simplest of the components:

# Add a ''Static Mesh Component'' parented under the ''Turret''
# Name it "Cannon"
# Move it into position, so that it looks good with the Turret

[[File:CannonComp Tank.jpg|left|970px]]
&lt;br clear=all>

===EventGraph===

# Create a ''Float Variable'' for holding the Cannons's ''Pitch'' rotation 
# Name it "Cannon Rot Pitch"
# Add an '''InputAxis MouseLookUp''' event
# Drag from the ''Axis Value'' and create an '''Float + Float''' node
# Make a '''Get''' for the ''Cannon Rot Pitch''
# Connect the ''Canon Rot Pitch'' into the ''Float + Float''
# Drag from the adding node and create a '''Clamp (Float)'''
# Set the '''Clamp's''' ''Min'' to 0 and ''Max'' to 45
# Create a '''Set Cannon Rot Pitch'''
# Connect it to the '''MouseLoopUp's''' ''Execution''
# Connect the '''Clamp's''' output to the '''Set Cannon Rot Pitch'''
# Create a '''Get''' for the ''Cannon'' Component
# Drag from the '''Get Cannon''' and create a '''Set Relative Rotation'''
# Connect the '''Set Cannon Rot Pitch''' to the '''Set Relative Rotation'''
# Drag from the '''Get Cannon''' and create a '''Get Relative Rotation'''
# Drag off '''Get Relative Rotation''' and create a '''Break Rot'''
# Drag off of the '''Break Rot''' and create a '''Make Rot'''
# Connect the ''Yaw'' and ''Roll'' values directly
# For the ''Pitch'' value, connect the '''Get Rot Pitch''' output
# Take the ''Return Value'' of the '''Make Rot''' and connect it with the '''Set Relative Rotation''' node's ''New Rotation'' input

[[File:CannonRotation Tank.jpg|left|970px]]
&lt;br clear=all>

'''''MORE TO COME! STAY TUNED!'''''
